# Database & Prisma Patterns

## Schema Conventions
- All models use `id` as UUID primary key with `@default(uuid())`
- Include `createdAt` and `updatedAt` timestamps on every model
- Use `@@map("snake_case_table")` for table names
- Use `@map("snake_case")` for column names that differ from camelCase fields
- Soft delete with `deletedAt DateTime?` — never hard delete user data

## Query Patterns
- Always use Prisma transactions for multi-table writes
- Use `select` or `include` explicitly — never fetch full objects when partial data suffices
- Paginate all list queries: require `take` and `skip` or cursor-based pagination
- Use Prisma middleware for audit logging

<example>
// ✅ Correct: explicit select, pagination, typed return
async function findUsers(page: number, pageSize: number): Promise<UserListItem[]> {
  return prisma.user.findMany({
    where: { deletedAt: null },
    select: { id: true, email: true, name: true, role: true },
    orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' },
    take: pageSize,
    skip: (page - 1) * pageSize,
  });
}
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// ❌ Wrong: fetches everything, no pagination, no soft-delete filter
async function findUsers() {
  return prisma.user.findMany();
}
</example>

## Migrations
- Always generate migration with descriptive name: `npx prisma migrate dev --name add_user_roles_table`
- Review generated SQL before applying
- Never edit migration files after they've been applied to staging/production
